GNOMERCY</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub114.ezboard.com/blegacyofsteel43089.showUserPublicProfile?gid=arlos>Arlos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Disciple</span><br>  Posts: 1866<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/10/03 2:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3790.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: wow</span><hr size=1> Jordan, for me, got very old VERY fast. Before long you could summarize the books like this: Start off with some plot, now we have character angst, more angst, yet more angst, still more angst, wow STILL more angst, Hey! some plot again, oops back to angst again, gee more angst, we haven't had angst in a while so more angst here, cliffhanger ending. Repeat for 6 or 7 more books.<br>
<br>
Tad Williams' Memory, Sorrow &amp; Thorn trilogy is probably the best fantasy I've read. <br>
<br>
George RR Martin's series (latest book is Storm of Swords, started out with Game of Thrones, I think it was) is not far below Tad Williams, though. I highly recommend it. Just be aware it can be a bit difficult to follow at first, as each chapter it keeps going back and forth to different characters.<br>
<br>
If you want semi sci-fi and like cyberpunk stuff, I can heartily recommend Snow Crash. Amazing book. Haven't liked the other stuff he's done as much, but that one is a must read.<br>
<br>
I never much cared for a lot of Asimov either. His early stuff was fine, but he really sucked later on. Caves of Steel was great, it's sequel was good, after that the series sucked. Foundation Trilogy was OK, though 2nd book was worse than 1st, and 3rd was worse than 2nd. The 4th foundation book (Foundation's Edge, I think) was just bad, and the final book, FOundation Earth or something, was quite possibly one of the WORST books I have EVER read. OMFG it was bad. Why in hell he felt compelled to tie the foundation series with the R Daneel Olivaw (ie, caves of steel) series in one Grand Unification Novel, I have no damn clue. Avoid that book like you'd avoid a 24-hour televangelist marathon on TV.<br>
<br>
Sword of Truth series is OK, though it goes downhill a fair bit after the first book. Wizard's First Rule is certainly quite good, but it got to be entirely too Jordan-esque for my taste. I never did finish the last book in the series I bothered buying. I guess the biggest issue I have with both is they have supposedly extremely intelligent people doing insanely stupid things (Gosh, he's been 100% right in everything he's said the last 28 times he's made pronouncements on things, but I don't believe him THIS time, so I'll do the opposite of what he says, and screw everything up!) so my suspension of disbelief goes right out the window.<br>
<br>
-Arlos <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub114.ezboard.com/blegacyofsteel43089.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tikker>Tikker</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Gnome Down!</span><br>  Posts: 2140<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/10/03 8:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3790.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: wow</span><hr size=1> arlos, you make me repeat myself<br>
