GNOMERCY</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub114.ezboard.com/blegacyofsteel43089.showUserPublicProfile?gid=denidivintia>DeniDivintia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>High Priestess</span><br>  Posts: 486<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/10/03 9:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3790.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Books</span><hr size=1> George RR Martin...an absolute MUST READ <p>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=470961</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub114.ezboard.com/blegacyofsteel43089.showUserPublicProfile?gid=barazonvaz>BarazonVaz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/14/03 1:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3790.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: wow</span><hr size=1> For great fantasy, I can't believe that no one has mentioned some of my favorites (after A Song of Fire and Ice, of course):<br>
<br>
The Amber series by Roger Zelazny is incredible, mysterious at first, hardcore fantasy all the way through.<br>
<br>
The Black Company by Glen Cook starts balls out, darkly humorous and a great read.  Slows down a little around Bleak Seasons, but worth finishing to find out the secrets at the end.  The bad guys are SO BAD, and the good guys are, well, pretty damn gray when they're at their best.<br>
<br>
The Taltos stories by Steven Brust.  Some of the earliest stuff is the best, when he's really into being an assassin.<br>
<br>
The Ethshar novels by Lawrence Watt-Evans, a little hard to find but incredible reading; The Misenchanted Sword and With a Single Spell are probably the best.  Also, his Lords of Dus series is a lot of fun.<br>
<br>
Fred Saberhagen's Books of Swords are a blast.  The first trilogy is wonderful, many of the others are great though there's one or two that fall short of his usual high standards.<br>
<br>
For great science fiction:<br>
<br>
Find used copies of 'The Science Fiction Hall of Fame' series if at all possible; these are voted on BY sci-fi writers, and include many classics all packed together: Nightfall, The Nine Billion Names of God, Flowers for Algernon, Who Goes There (from which the movies 'The Thing' were made), etc etc.<br>
<br>
The Mote in God's Eye, by Niven and Pournelle is a Hugo award winner that does one of the finest jobs ever of making an alien race that is VERY alien, with motivations very different than humans.  Also their Ringworld novels are very fun.  Lucifer's Hammer is supposed to be great, it's on my stack to read soon.<br>
<br>
Anything by Robert L Forward, if you like your science fiction so hard that it needs a 30 page technical appendix to explain things like antimatter and time travel to the non-physicist reader.  Start with Dragon's Egg.  He also wrote a book, Indistinguishable from Magic, about things which seem like science fiction but are not: antimatter (created on Earth, every day, on purpose), time travel (we know HOW, actually MAKING one is a little beyond us), etc.<br>
<br>
Authors that span both genres: Ursula K LeGuin and CJ Cherryh.  LeGuin is the first (and I _think_ still only) author to win BOTH the Hugo and Nebula awards for more than one book (The Left Hand of Darkness and The Dispossed).  CJ Cherryh is both prolific and superb.  Her Morgaine Saga is great fun, Cyteen and Downbelow Station are scifi hallmarks, and the excellent Faded Sun trilogy was recently reprinted.<br>
<br>
Bah, I could go on all day!<br>
<br>
Barazon <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub114.ezboard.com/blegacyofsteel43089.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tikker>Tikker</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Gnome Down!</span><br>  Posts: 2148<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/14/03 5:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3790.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: wow</span><hr size=1> yeah, the black company was pretty good for the 1st 4 or 5 books<br>
